    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1958-09-26T14:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1958-09-26T14:00:00-05:00" n="46"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d46">
                <head>46. Memorandum of Conversation<note n="0" type="source" xml:id="d46fn0"
                        >Source: Department of State, Secretary’s Memoranda of Conversation: Lot 64
                        D199. Secret; Presidential Handling. Drafted by <persName corresp="#p_GJNJ1"
                            >Greene</persName>. This meeting was held at the Waldorf Astoria.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <gloss target="#t_MC1">MC</gloss>-12</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>New York</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            type="conversation-or-meeting-date" when="1958-09-26T15:00:00-04:00"
                            >September 26, 1958, 3 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="center">SECRETARY’S TRIP TO NEW YORK<note n="1" xml:id="d46fn1">
                        <persName corresp="#p_DJF1">Dulles</persName> was in New York to deliver a
                        speech.</note>
                </p>
                <list type="participants">
                    <head>PARTICIPANTS</head>
                    <item>
                        <hi rend="italic">United States</hi>
                        <list>
                            <item>The Secretary</item>
                            <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_GJNJ1">Greene</persName>
                            </item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <hi rend="italic">France</hi>
                        <list>
                            <item>Foreign Minister <persName corresp="#p_CMM1">Couve de
                                    Murville</persName>
                            </item>
                            <item>Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_AH1">Hervé Alphand</persName>
                            </item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Expansion of <gloss target="#t_NATO1">NATO</gloss>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <p>The Secretary referred to General <persName corresp="#p_DEGC1">de
                        Gaulle</persName>’s letter of September 17 to President <persName
                        corresp="#p_EDD1">Eisenhower</persName>
                    <note n="2" xml:id="d46fn2">
                        <ref target="#d45">Document 45</ref>.</note> and recalled that he had
                    explained to Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_AH1">Alphand</persName> that it
                    raised major problems which would have to be carefully studied within the United
                    States Government.<note n="3" xml:id="d46fn3">The memorandum of <persName
                            corresp="#p_DAW1">Dulles</persName>’ conversation with <persName
                            corresp="#p_AH1">Alphand</persName> on September 25 has not been found,
                        but see the source note, <ref target="#d45">Document 45</ref>.</note> It
                    seemed to the Secretary that the proposal represents a search for a more
                    responsible and dependable way to deal with the problems of the world, or at
                    least a part of it, than is now offered by the United Nations. He noted that the
                    United States Government has been giving thought to the future of the United
                    Nations just because its prospects do seem dim. The Foreign Minister said that
                    he thought General <persName corresp="#p_DEGC1">de Gaulle</persName> was
                    concerned with how better to organize the Western world and the Western
                    alliance.</p>
                <p>The Foreign Minister told the Secretary that General <persName corresp="#p_DEGC1"
                        >de Gaulle</persName> had showed to <persName corresp="#p_SPH1"
                        >Spaak</persName>, in greatest confidence, his (<persName corresp="#p_DEGC1"
                        >de Gaulle</persName>’s) memorandum which he had sent to President <persName
                        corresp="#p_EDD1">Eisenhower</persName> and Prime Minister <persName
                        corresp="#p_MH1">Macmillan</persName> on September 17.<note n="4"
                        xml:id="d46fn4">
                        <persName corresp="#p_DAW1">Dulles</persName> discussed the <persName
                            corresp="#p_DEGC1">de Gaulle</persName> memorandum with <persName
                            corresp="#p_NGL1">Norstad</persName> that morning; see <ref
                            target="frus1958-60v07p1#d156">Part 1, Document 156</ref>.</note>
                </p>
            </div>
